Help on skill:     Frenzy
Usage duration:    1 round
Fatigue:           low
Skill type:        attack
Affecting stat(s): strength, constitution, dexterity, anatomy, spot weakness,
critical and skill percent
Trained fighters pace themselves. They calculate. They measure each strike,
conserving energy for prolonged combat. The barbarian does not.
There comes a moment when control becomes a luxury you cannot afford, when
the only path to victory is through overwhelming, relentless violence. Your
weapon becomes a blur. One strike flows into the next without pause, without
thought, without mercy. Again. Again. Again. A cascade of steel that gives
no quarter, no moment to recover, no breath to defend.
This is not fighting - this is drowning your enemy in brutality. They cannot
block all the strikes. Cannot dodge every blow. Cannot distinguish where one
attack ends and the next begins. By the time the storm passes, they stand
bleeding from wounds they never saw coming, their defense shattered by the
sheer impossible speed of savage fury.
Civilization teaches restraint. The frenzy teaches victory.
Using this skill costs five points of fury.
---------------------------------------------------
Help on skill:     Intimidating presence
Usage duration:    random
Fatigue:           low
Skill type:        special
Affecting stat(s): constitution, strength, skill percent, leadership and inner
strength
Reputation intimidates. Scars intimidate. But a true Warbringer projects
menace as something more tangible, more immediate. It radiates from your
scarred flesh, your unwavering stance, the cold certainty in your eyes that
says you have seen death a thousand times and sent it away disappointed.
When you consciously channel this aura, enemies hesitate. Their strikes
falter. They pull back at the last moment. They aim for less vital spots,
not from mercy, but from primal fear. The kind that makes prey reconsider
attacking a predator. This is not magic. This is pure, distilled menace
given form, making you a fortress that enemies batter themselves against
with decreasing conviction.
Using this skill costs three points of fury.
---------------------------------------------------
Help on skill:     Last stand
Usage duration:    random
Fatigue:           low
Skill type:        special
Affecting stat(s): constitution, skill percent, inner strength and endurance
Death comes for everyone. Most warriors accept this inevitability when
wounds become too grave, when blood loss becomes too severe. A Warbringer
knows better. Even when your body screams for mercy, when blood pools at
your feet, when enemies smell victory, you have one final refusal left.
Drawing upon reserves you did not know existed, fueled by pure stubborn
defiance, you plant your feet and declare: not yet. Not here. Not to you.
Your wounds seem to matter less. Your armor feels heavier on their weapons
than on your shoulders. Your body remembers how to mend itself even as you
fight. This is what separates the Warbringer from ordinary warriors.
Everyone can fight when fresh. You fight hardest when you should already
be dead.
Using this skill costs three points of fury.
---------------------------------------------------
Help on skill:     Overpower
Usage duration:    automatic
Skill type:        passive
Affecting stat(s): strength and skill percent
Civilized warriors falter when their strikes miss. They adjust, recalculate,
hesitate. The barbarian does not. Each dodge teaches. Each parry reveals.
Each tumbling escape maps the enemy's patterns. Failure is not setback - it
is reconnaissance written in the language of violence.
Where others see frustration in a blocked strike, the savage sees opening.
That sidestep showed weight distribution. That parry revealed reach and
reaction speed. That tumble displayed timing. The prey has shown its dance,
and predators learn fast.
The next strike comes differently - heavier, faster, from an unexpected
angle. Techniques that worked moments ago suddenly fail. The barbarian
adapts with brutal efficiency, overwhelming defensive patterns through raw
physical dominance and learned advantage.
Miss once, twice - it matters not. The barbarian will overpower.
