Help on skill:     Relentless advance
Usage duration:    random
Fatigue:           very low
Skill type:        attack
Affecting stat(s): strength, constitution, attack, anatomy, spot weakness and
skill percent
Trained soldiers retreat when wounded. Tactical withdrawal, they call it.
Strategic repositioning. The berserker knows what they refuse to admit:
these are just polite words for cowardice.
You do not retreat. You do not reposition. You advance. Always forward,
never back. Arrows find you? Advance. Spells strike you? Advance. The
enemy lands a perfect blow that should drop you? Absorb it and advance.
Pain is temporary. Momentum is survival. To stop moving forward is to
acknowledge your enemy as a threat worth avoiding.
Every impact you take feeds the rage. Every wound makes you more dangerous,
not less. Where civilized warriors see injury and think of healing, you see
fuel for the fury that propels you into striking range. By the time you
reach your enemy, you have transformed their attacks into your own power.
The berserker does not stop. The berserker arrives.
Using this skill generates two points of fury.
---------------------------------------------------
Help on skill:     Rending strike
Usage duration:    1 round
Fatigue:           mediocre
Skill type:        attack
Affecting stat(s): strength, constitution, anatomy, spot weakness, critical and
skill percent
Swordmasters practice clean cuts. Precise. Elegant. Minimal damage for
maximum effect, they claim. The barbarian understands what they refuse to
see: elegance is weakness. Your enemy doesn't need a clean death. They
need to be ruined. To be bled out.
You don't simply cut. You rend. The initial strike is just the beginning.
As your weapon bites deep, you twist. Wrench. Turn a wound into catastrophe.
Muscle tears away from bone. Tendons snap like rotted rope. What was a
functional body becomes a ruin of separated parts still attached by stubborn
threads of tissue.
Where civilized fighters aim for quick kills, you aim for devastation. Your
enemy will not just fall, they will break. Not just die, they will be
torn apart. The difference between striking and rending is the difference
between injury and destruction.
What was whole becomes ruined. This is the barbarian way.
Using this skill costs five or more points of fury.
